"   <div id=\"basicsTopicLeft\">",
"    <div id=\"topicTitle\">",
"     Patient information: Prolactinoma (The Basics)",
"    </div>",
"    <span class=\"view\">",
"     View in",
"     <a class=\"lang\" href=\"./es-419/prolactinoma-the-basics?source=topic_page\">",
"      Spanish",
"     </a>",
"    </span>",
"    <a class=\"contributor contributor_credentials\" href=\"./authors-and-editors/patient-information\">",
"     Written by the doctors and editors at UpToDate",
"    </a>",
"    <div id=\"topicText\">",
"     <p class=\"headingAnchor\" id=\"H2407954\">",
"      <span class=\"h1\">",
"       What are prolactinomas?",
"      </span>",
"      &nbsp;&mdash;&nbsp;Prolactinomas are abnormal growths that form right below the brain, in an organ called the &ldquo;pituitary gland&rdquo; (",
"      <a class=\"graphic graphic_figure graphicRef72262 \" href=\"UTD.htm?38/36/39503\">",
"       figure 1",
"      </a>",
"      ). These growths can cause symptoms, such as absent monthly periods in women or low sex drive in men.",
"     </p>",
"     <p>",
"      The pituitary gland has different cells in it that make different hormones. Some of the cells in the pituitary gland make a hormone called &ldquo;prolactin.&rdquo;",
"     </p>",
"     <p>",
"      A prolactinoma forms when these cells change into abnormal cells and grow out of control. When that happens, the body&rsquo;s prolactin levels can get too high.",
"     </p>",
"     <p>",
"      Prolactinomas can cause symptoms in 2 ways. Symptoms can happen when:",
"     </p>",
"     <p>",
"      <ul class=\"bulletCompact-block\">",
"       <li>",
"        A person has too much prolactin &mdash; This can throw off the levels of other hormones.",
"       </li>",
"       <li>",
"        A prolactinoma grows and presses on nearby tissues in the head, such as the nerves that go from the eyes to the brain",
"       </li>",
"      </ul>",
"     </p>",
"     <p>",
"      Prolactinomas can grow in both men and women. They are most common in women younger than 50 years old.",
"     </p>",
"     <p class=\"headingAnchor\" id=\"H2407961\">",
"      <span class=\"h1\">",
"       What are the symptoms of a prolactinoma?",
"      </span>",
"      &nbsp;&mdash;&nbsp;Too much prolactin can cause symptoms in men and in women who still get their monthly periods. (Women who no longer get their monthly periods do not get these symptoms.) Symptoms can include:",
"     </p>",
"     <p>",
"      <ul class=\"bulletCompact-block\">",
"       <li>",
"        Absent or irregular monthly periods (in women)",
"       </li>",
"       <li>",
"        Trouble starting a pregnancy (in men and women)",
"       </li>",
"       <li>",
"        Milk leaking from the breasts (in women)",
"       </li>",
"       <li>",
"        Vaginal dryness and hot flashes (in women)",
"       </li>",
"       <li>",
"        Low energy, low sex drive, and trouble getting an erection (in men)",
"       </li>",
"       <li>",
"        Increase in breast size and breast soreness (in men)",
"       </li>",
"       <li>",
"        Bone loss (in men and women) &mdash; This takes a few years to happen.",
"       </li>",
"      </ul>",
"     </p>",
"     <p>",
"      When a prolactinoma presses on nearby tissues, it can cause:",
"     </p>",
"     <p>",
"      <ul class=\"bulletCompact-block\">",
"       <li>",
"        Vision problems",
"       </li>",
"       <li>",
"        Headaches",
"       </li>",
"       <li>",
"        Lower levels of other hormones that are made in the pituitary gland",
"       </li>",
"      </ul>",
"     </p>",
"     <p class=\"headingAnchor\" id=\"H2407968\">",
"      <span class=\"h1\">",
"       Is there a test for a prolactinoma?",
"      </span>",
"      &nbsp;&mdash;&nbsp;Yes. Your doctor or nurse can do:",
"     </p>",
"     <p>",
"      <ul class=\"bulletCompact-block\">",
"       <li>",
"        A blood test to measure the level of prolactin in your body",
"       </li>",
"       <li>",
"        An imaging test called an MRI &mdash; Imaging tests create pictures of the inside of the body.",
"       </li>",
"      </ul>",
"     </p>",
"     <p class=\"headingAnchor\" id=\"H2407975\">",
"      <span class=\"h1\">",
"       How are prolactinomas treated?",
"      </span>",
"      &nbsp;&mdash;&nbsp;Prolactinomas are treated in different ways, depending on their size, the symptoms they cause, and other factors. Small prolactinomas that cause no symptoms do not usually need to be treated. Big prolactinomas that cause symptoms do need to be treated.",
"     </p>",
"     <p>",
"      Prolactinomas that need treatment are usually first treated with medicines called &ldquo;dopamine agonists.&rdquo; These medicines can shrink prolactinomas and lower prolactin levels to normal. When the prolactin levels get back to normal, most symptoms get better. People usually take these medicines for years.",
"     </p>",
"     <p>",
"      If these medicines do not work or cause too many side effects, there are other treatment options. These can include:",
"     </p>",
"     <p>",
"      <ul class=\"bullet-block\">",
"       <li>",
"        Surgery to remove the prolactinoma &mdash; Sometimes, doctors recommend surgery first. For example, women who have a big prolactinoma and want to get pregnant might be treated with surgery first.",
"       </li>",
"       <li>",
"        Other types of medicines",
"       </li>",
"      </ul>",
"     </p>",
"     <p class=\"headingAnchor\" id=\"H2407982\">",
"      <span class=\"h1\">",
"       What if I want to get pregnant?",
"      </span>",
"      &nbsp;&mdash;&nbsp;If you want to get pregnant, talk with your doctor about the right treatment for you. Many women are able to get pregnant after treatment.",
"     </p>",
"     <p>",
"      Women who take dopamine agonist medicines must stop taking them during pregnancy. But without these medicines, their prolactinomas can start to grow.",
"     </p>",
"     <p>",
"      If you stop your medicines, tell your doctor or nurse about any vision changes or new or worse headaches. Having those symptoms could mean that your prolactinoma has grown. If that happens, your doctor will talk with you about possible treatments.",
"     </p>",
"     <p class=\"headingAnchor\" id=\"H2407989\">",
"      <span class=\"h1\">",
"       What if I go through menopause?",
"      </span>",
"      &nbsp;&mdash;&nbsp;If you are being treated for a prolactinoma and go through menopause, talk with your doctor or nurse. Some women can stop their treatment after menopause.",
"     </p>",
